{"title_page": "Steve Lauri", "text_new": "[[File:Steve Lauri PR photo.jpg|thumb|Steve Lauri, Singer, Songwriter and Guitarist\nCurrent member of The Hollies\n]]\n'''Steve Lauri''' (26 April 1954) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] singer and guitarist.  He is a member of the British band, [[The Hollies]].<ref>[http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/leisure/boltonmusic/music_reviews/10310457.Live_Review__The_Hollies___Lowry_Theatre__Salford___22_3_13/?ref=rss  \"Live Review: The Hollies - Lowry Theatre, Salford - 22/3/13\"]. ''The Bolton News'' 24 March 2013 in Music Reviews by Martin Hutchinson.</ref><ref>[http://www.gloucestercitizen.co.uk/Review-Hollies-Cheltenham-Town-Hall/story-18492399-detail/story.html \"Review: The Hollies, Cheltenham Town Hall\"]. ''Gloucester Citizen''.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nLauri was born in [[London]].  He began performing professionally in the mid seventies.\n\n==Career==\nLauri started his working life as an apprentice in the avionics industry with GEC Avionics in Rochestr Kent, but quit to pursue his profesional music career\nLauri worked briefly on U.S. Army and Air Force bases in Germany, and then moved on to the London pub circuit.  In 1977 he joined pop disco group 5000 Volts,<ref>[https://www.yumpu.com/de/document/view/23328946/goodtimes-music-from-the-60s-to-the-80s-the-who-vorschau/37 \"CD REVIEWS RAY WILSON CHA\"]. ''Good Times'', via Yumpu.</ref> and the group toured the UK, Europe, Scandinavia and South Africa and had two top ten hits while Lauri was with them. They also supported the Stylistics on their British tour, including their performance at the Royal Albert Hall.\n\nIn 1979 Lauri joined the Bonnie Tyler Band as a singing guitarist, touring Europe and America to promote ''It's a Heartache'', Tyler's second hit single.\n\nIn 1980 Steve joined Sprinkler, the resident band at The Green Man pub in southeast London, where he performed  until the mid-eighties, when the band was called upon as session/backing players to the hit group Bucks Fizz. Lauri took part in many UK and European tours with them, and was injured in the Bucks Fizz coach crash.\n\nLauri joined the newly formed Cliff Richard Band in 1987. He toured with Richard for three years, including visits to New Zealand, Australia and Europe, and recorded with the band on the album ''Thief in the Night''.<ref>[http://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/244335/hollies-revel-dunedin-sun \"Hollies revel in Dunedin sun\"]. ''Otego Daily Times.''</ref><ref name=\"Rust2010\">{{cite book|author=Victor Rust|title=The Cliff Richard Recording Catalogue 1958-2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HyijAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA541|year=2010|publisher=Rust|isbn=978-0-9567384-0-0|pages=541\u2013}}</ref> Lauri took part in the concert called The Event at the now demolished Wembley Stadium.\n\nIn the early nineties Lauri toured with Elaine Paige, again as guitarist/vocalist.  He later worked with glam rockers the Glitter Band, both touring and in the recording studio.\n\nFrom 1996 to 1999 Steve worked in various theatres, playing guitar for comedian Billy Pearce, singer David Essex, and as part of comedy duo Hale n' Pace's backing band. Also in the nineties he played at many recording sessions at Pelican Studios, which was part owned by Ray Stiles, bass guitarist with The Hollies.\n\nLauri joined The Hollies in 2004 as a singer and guitarist,<ref>[http://www.dailyinfo.co.uk/reviews/feature/2405/The_Hollies \"The Hollies\"]. ''Daily Info''</ref><ref name=fifty>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/leisure/music/11846184.Hollies_still_going_strong_after_50_years_of_music_with_tour_stop_in_Hampshire/ \"Hollies turn back clock; REVIEWS The Hollies SYMPHONY HALL.\"]. ''Southern Echo''., also ''Birmingham Post & Mail'', via The Free Library.</ref> and is a contributor to the harmonies for which The Hollies are known.<ref>[http://www.nottinghampost.com/Interview-Hollies-promise-hit-fest-Royal-Concert/story-26229439-detail/story.html \"Interview: The Hollies promise 'hit-fest' at Royal Concert Hall gig\"].  ''Nottingham Post'' March 25, 2015</ref><ref>Graham Reid. [http://www.elsewhere.co.nz/absoluteelsewhere/3851/the-hollies-tony-hicks-interviewed-2010-the-road-is-long/ \"THE HOLLIES. TONY HICKS INTERVIEWED (2010): The road is long . . .\"]. ''Elsewhere by Graham Reid''.</ref>  He recorded with The Hollies on their studio albums, ''Staying Power'' and ''Then, Now and Always'', as well as their double CD titled, ''Hollies Live Hits, We Got the Tunes''.\n\nLaurie has been part of the Hollies tour since 2004.<ref name=fifty /> On tour he is the featured singer on several of their hits, including ''King Midas in Reverse'' and ''Here I Go Again''.  He performed with the band during their 50th anniversary tour in 2012,<ref>[http://www.edinburghguide.com/reviews/music/folk/thehollies50thanniversarytourreview-10318 \"The Hollies 50th Anniversary Tour Review\"]. ''Edinburgh Guide'', Irene Brown on 23 April 2012</ref> as well as on the following album, ''Fifty at 50''.<ref>[http://renownedforsound.com/index.php/album-review-the-hollies-50-at-fifty/ \"Album Review: The Hollies \u2013 50 at Fifty\"]. ''Renowned for Sound'', October 7, 2014 | By Aisleen Evans\n</ref>\n\nLauri performs as a solo artist when not on tour with the band.  He has written and recorded many original songs,<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/local/wp/2013/08/08/the-fairfax-tuba-guy-gets-his-own-song-courtesy-of-one-of-the-hollies/ \"The Fairfax \u2018Tuba Guy\u2019 gets his own song, courtesy of one of the Hollies\"]. ''Washington Post'', Tom Jackman August 8, 2013.</ref> and released his first solo CD in 2012, titled ''At Last''. He toured the USA in support of this CD and subsequently recorded a second album, ''Curfew''.<ref>[http://wjla.com/news/entertainment/steve-lauri--22680 \"Steve Lauri's new album\"]. ''WJLA'' By Fasia Hardy, August 8th 2014</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.hollies.co.uk\n*http://www.stevelaurimusic.com\n*http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-hollies-mn0000087985/biography\n*http://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-lauri-mn0001740860 -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauri, Steve}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Steve Lauri PR photo.jpg|thumb|Steve Lauri, Singer, Songwriter and Guitarist\nCurrent member of The Hollies\n]]\n'''Steve Lauri''' (26 April 1954) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] singer and guitarist.  He is a member of the British band, [[The Hollies]].<ref>[http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/leisure/boltonmusic/music_reviews/10310457.Live_Review__The_Hollies___Lowry_Theatre__Salford___22_3_13/?ref=rss  \"Live Review: The Hollies - Lowry Theatre, Salford - 22/3/13\"]. ''The Bolton News'' 24 March 2013 in Music Reviews by Martin Hutchinson. </ref><ref>[http://www.gloucestercitizen.co.uk/Review-Hollies-Cheltenham-Town-Hall/story-18492399-detail/story.html \"Review: The Hollies, Cheltenham Town Hall\"]. ''Gloucester Citizen''. </ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nLauri was born in [[London]].  He began performing professionally in the mid seventies. \n\n==Career==\nLauri started his working life as an apprentice in the avionics industry with GEC Avionics in Rochestr Kent. but quit to pursue his proffessionel music career\nLauri worked briefly on U.S. Army and Air Force bases in Germany, and then moved on to the London pub circuit.  In 1977 he joined pop disco group 5000 Volts,<ref>[https://www.yumpu.com/de/document/view/23328946/goodtimes-music-from-the-60s-to-the-80s-the-who-vorschau/37 \"CD REVIEWS RAY WILSON CHA\"]. ''Good Times'', via Yumpu.</ref> and the group toured the UK, Europe, Scandinavia and South Africa and had two top ten hits while Lauri was with them. They also supported the Stylistics on their British tour, including their performance at the Royal Albert Hall.\n\nIn 1979 Lauri joined the Bonnie Tyler Band as a singing guitarist, touring Europe and America to promote ''It's a Heartache'', Tyler's second hit single.  \n\nIn 1980 Steve joined Sprinkler, the resident band at The Green Man pub in southeast London, where he performed  until the mid-eighties, when the band was called upon as session/backing players to the hit group Bucks Fizz. Lauri took part in many UK and European tours with them, and was injured in the Bucks Fizz coach crash.  \n\nLauri joined the newly formed Cliff Richard Band in 1987. He toured with Richard for three years, including visits to New Zealand, Australia and Europe, and recorded with the band on the album ''Thief in the Night''.<ref>[http://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/244335/hollies-revel-dunedin-sun \"Hollies revel in Dunedin sun\"]. ''Otego Daily Times.'' </ref><ref name=\"Rust2010\">{{cite book|author=Victor Rust|title=The Cliff Richard Recording Catalogue 1958-2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HyijAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA541|year=2010|publisher=Rust|isbn=978-0-9567384-0-0|pages=541\u2013}}</ref> Lauri took part in the concert called The Event at the now demolished Wembley Stadium.\n\nIn the early nineties Lauri toured with Elaine Paige, again as guitarist/vocalist.  He later worked with glam rockers the Glitter Band, both touring and in the recording studio. \n\nFrom 1996 to 1999 Steve worked in various theatres, playing guitar for comedian Billy Pearce, singer David Essex, and as part of comedy duo Hale n' Pace's backing band. Also in the nineties he played at many recording sessions at Pelican Studios, which was part owned by Ray Stiles, bass guitarist with The Hollies.\n\nLauri joined The Hollies in 2004 as a singer and guitarist,<ref>[http://www.dailyinfo.co.uk/reviews/feature/2405/The_Hollies \"The Hollies\"]. ''Daily Info''</ref><ref name=fifty>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/leisure/music/11846184.Hollies_still_going_strong_after_50_years_of_music_with_tour_stop_in_Hampshire/ \"Hollies turn back clock; REVIEWS The Hollies SYMPHONY HALL.\"]. ''Southern Echo''., also ''Birmingham Post & Mail'', via The Free Library.</ref> and is a contributor to the harmonies for which The Hollies are known.<ref>[http://www.nottinghampost.com/Interview-Hollies-promise-hit-fest-Royal-Concert/story-26229439-detail/story.html \"Interview: The Hollies promise 'hit-fest' at Royal Concert Hall gig\"].  ''Nottingham Post'' March 25, 2015</ref><ref>Graham Reid. [http://www.elsewhere.co.nz/absoluteelsewhere/3851/the-hollies-tony-hicks-interviewed-2010-the-road-is-long/ \"THE HOLLIES. TONY HICKS INTERVIEWED (2010): The road is long . . .\"]. ''Elsewhere by Graham Reid''. </ref>  He recorded with The Hollies on their studio albums, ''Staying Power'' and ''Then, Now and Always'', as well as their double CD titled, ''Hollies Live Hits, We Got the Tunes''.\n\nLaurie has been part of the Hollies tour since 2004.<ref name=fifty /> On tour he is the featured singer on several of their hits, including ''King Midas in Reverse'' and ''Here I Go Again''.  He performed with the band during their 50th anniversary tour in 2012,<ref>[http://www.edinburghguide.com/reviews/music/folk/thehollies50thanniversarytourreview-10318 \"The Hollies 50th Anniversary Tour Review\"]. ''Edinburgh Guide'', Irene Brown on 23 April 2012</ref> as well as on the following album, ''Fifty at 50''.<ref>[http://renownedforsound.com/index.php/album-review-the-hollies-50-at-fifty/ \"Album Review: The Hollies \u2013 50 at Fifty\"]. ''Renowned for Sound'', October 7, 2014 | By Aisleen Evans\n</ref>\n\nLauri performs as a solo artist when not on tour with the band.  He has written and recorded many original songs,<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/local/wp/2013/08/08/the-fairfax-tuba-guy-gets-his-own-song-courtesy-of-one-of-the-hollies/ \"The Fairfax \u2018Tuba Guy\u2019 gets his own song, courtesy of one of the Hollies\"]. ''Washington Post'', Tom Jackman August 8, 2013.</ref> and released his first solo CD in 2012, titled ''At Last''. He toured the USA in support of this CD and subsequently recorded a second album, ''Curfew''.<ref>[http://wjla.com/news/enter